    "statement": "William of Sherwood (Guilelmus, Willelmus, Schyrwode, Shirwode, Shyreswode, and others) was a 13th century English logician who taught at the University of Paris and who worked in the Realist tradition of logic. His Introduction to Logic , written in the middle of the century, was one of the four most influential textbooks on logics in the 13th century, along with Lambert of Auxerre's Summary , Roger Bacon's Art and Science of Logic , and Peter of Spain's Summaries of Logic . Roger Bacon in his Opus tertium (1267) singles Sherwood out for high praise, describing him as \"much wiser than Albert [the Great]; for in philosophia communis no one is greater than he\" (Kretzmann 1966, pp. 5-6; Kretzmann 1968, pp. 3-4).",
    "context": "Opening section: 1. Life and writing | Related entries: roger-bacon, lambert-auxerre, obligationes, peter-spain, square, medieval-terms",
